Since 2001, several cases of '''detention and search of Indian VIPs at US airports''' have been reported, resulting in diplomatic tensions between India and the United States. Protest from Indian authorities often led to apologies from US officials. Unlike the United States, India frequently exempts diplomats and other well-known figures from airport security checks.<ref name="hsp" />
Bollywood superstar [[Shah Rukh Khan]] was at the centre of three well-publicised incidents. On 15 August 2009, he was detained at [[Newark Liberty International Airport|Newark]] while on his way to celebrate [[Independence Day (India)|India's Independence Day]] in Chicago.<ref name="srk09">{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2009/08/15/AR2009081501595.html |title=Indian Actor's Questioning at Airport Draws Criticism|first=Emily|last=Wax|newspaper=[[The Washington Post]]|date=16 August 2009|accessdate=12 March 2016}}</ref> Three years later, he was stopped at [[Westchester County Airport|New York White Plains]] where he had landed to address a conference at [[Yale University]].<ref name="srk12">{{cite news|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/bollywood/news/Shah-Rukh-Khans-detention-US-apologises-India-talks-tough/articleshow/12648019.cms |title=Shah Rukh Khan's detention: US apologises, India talks tough|newspaper=[[The Times of India]]|date=13 April 2012|accessdate=12 March 2016}}</ref> Four years later again, he was stopped at Los Angeles International Airport. <ref name="ti20160812">{{cite news|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/Shah-Rukh-Khan-detained-at-Los-Angeles-airport/articleshow/53662583.cms |title=Shah Rukh Khan detained at Los Angeles airport|newspaper=[[The Times of India]]|date=12 August 2016|accessdate=12 August 2016}}</ref>
In December 2010, Indian Ambassador to the United States [[Meera Shankar]] and to the United Nations [[Hardeep Singh Puri]] were both targeted by security agents in two separate incidents.<ref name="ms">{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-south-asia-11957943 |title=India's ambassador Meera Shankar frisked at US airport|publisher=[[BBC]] |date=9 December 2010|accessdate=12 March 2016}}</ref><ref name="hsp">{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/asia/india/8199063/Indian-UN-ambassador-detained-at-airport-for-refusing-to-remove-turban.html |title=Indian UN ambassador detained at airport for refusing to remove turban|newspaper=[[The Daily Telegraph|The Telegraph]]|date=13 December 2010|accessdate=12 March 2016}}</ref> In September 2011, former President of India [[A. P. J. Abdul Kalam]] was searched twice – before and after boarding his plane – at [[John F. Kennedy International Airport|New York JFK]] airport.<ref name="apjak">{{cite news|url=http://www.ibtimes.com/us-officials-sacked-frisking-indias-former-president-did-tsa-go-too-far-371782 |title=U.S. Officials Sacked for Frisking India’s Former President; Did TSA Go Too Far?|first=Sanskrity |last=Sinha|newspaper=[[International Business Times]]|date=18 November 2011|accessdate=12 March 2016}}</ref>
In 2015, it was announced that a list of 2,000 Indian VIPs will be included in the US [[Global Entry]] programme, which warrants expedited clearance at US airports. The list was to include former Presidents and Prime Ministers, prominent industrialists and movie stars.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://indiatoday.intoday.in/story/us-airports-will-now-treat-2000-indians-as-vvips/1/473818.html |title=US airports will now treat 2,000 Indians as VVIPS|first=Abhishek |last=Bhalla |newspaper=[[India Today]]|date=15 September 2015|accessdate=12 March 2016}}</ref>
