[[File:Aymar-Varney.PNG|thumb|''Aymar-Vernay dowsing with a divining rod.'']]
'''Jacques Aymar-Vernay''' (born in 1662) was a stonemason from the village of [[Saint-Marcellin, Isère|Saint Marcellin]] in [[Dauphiné]], [[France]], who reintroduced [[dowsing]] with a [[divining rod]] into popular usage in [[Europe]]. He claimed to have discovered springs and treasures hiding in the earth using his rod, and even tracked down criminals using it. According to some accounts, when he neared the scene of a murder using a divining rod, he would break into a sweat, shudder, and in some instances, even faint.
In 1692, Aymar-Vernay was hired by authorities to locate a murderer. By swinging a [[pendulum]] he identified a 19-year-old boy, a [[Kyphosis|hunchback]], as the culprit. The boy was subsequently "[[breaking wheel|broken on the wheel]]" (tortuously executed).<ref name="flimflam">{{cite book | last = Randi | first = James | authorlink = James Randi | title = Flim-Flam! Psychics, ESP, Unicorns, and Other Delusions | publisher = [[Prometheus Books]] | year = 1982 | isbn = 0-87975-198-3 }}</ref> Aymar subsequently became something of a national celebrity for his "ability". When submitting to testing by [[Prince de Condé]], however, he failed every single test.<ref name="flimflam" />
